<p>That the appendix is subject to many of the diseases afflicting the gastrointestinal tract is well known.<sup><xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr1-1066896912444161">1</xref></sup> Of perhaps lesser importance but also well documented are reports of its function and idiosyncrasies regarding its length. The current record for the lengthiest appendix is cited at a staggering 55 cm.<sup><xref ref-type="bibr" rid="bibr2-1066896912444161">2</xref></sup></p>
<p>However, reports on its demeanor, except perhaps in clinical terms, are lacking in the pathology literature. This appendix addresses this topic as the undoubted angriest specimen to date (<xref ref-type="fig" rid="fig1-1066896912444161">Figures 1</xref> and <xref ref-type="fig" rid="fig2-1066896912444161">2</xref>).</p>
